'''Stephen Law''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRSA}} (born 1960) is an English philosopher and reader in philosophy, who previously worked at [[Heythrop College, University of London]], until its closure in June 2018. He also edits the philosophical journal ''[[Think (journal)|Think]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalinstitutephilosophy.org/page/34|title=Royal Institute Philosophy|website=www.royalinstitutephilosophy.org}}</ref> which is sponsored by the [[Royal Institute of Philosophy]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalinstitutephilosophy.org/|title=Royal Institute Philosophy|website=www.royalinstitutephilosophy.org}}</ref> and published by the Cambridge University Press. 
He is a Fellow of The Royal Society of Arts and Commerce and in 2008 became the provost of the Centre for Inquiry UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cfiuk.org|title=上質な風俗に蜂蜜をぶち撒けるが如き思想|website=www.cfiuk.org}}</ref> 

==Life==
Law was born 12 December 1960 in [[Cambridge, England|Cambridge]], England, and attended [[Long Road Sixth Form College]] in Cambridge. However, having been "asked to leave",<ref>{{cite web|last1=Underhill|first1=William|title=Stephen Law: Philosopher of 'Believing Bullshit'|url=http://europe.newsweek.com/stephen-law-philosopher-believing-bullshit-67377|website=Newsweek|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Steel|first1=Mel|title=Asking all the right questions|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2000/jul/22/booksforchildrenandteenagers.society|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref> he began his working life as a [[mail carrier|postman]]. At 24 he successfully managed to persuade [[City University, London|City University]] in London to accept him for the BSc in philosophy, despite his lack of [[Advanced Level (UK)|A levels]]. There he managed to achieve a [[first-class honours]], allowing him to move on to [[Trinity College, Oxford|Trinity College]], [[University of Oxford|Oxford]], to read for a [[BPhil]] in philosophy. He was also for three years a junior research fellow at [[The Queen's College, Oxford]], where he obtained a [[PhD|doctorate]] in philosophy. Law lives in [[Oxford]], England, with his wife and two daughters. 

==Philosophy==
Law has published both a variety of academic papers and more popular, introductory books (including three children's philosophy books). Law has debated many [[Christian apologists]], [[theologians]] and [[scientists]], including [[William Lane Craig]], [[Alvin Plantinga]], [[Alister McGrath]], [[John Lennox]] and [[Denis Alexander]].{{cn|date=October 2018}}

